== Tangy Mayo ==

Wash and dry produce.

Quarter @lemon{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @ketchup{1}, half the @mayonnaise{4%tbsp}, half the @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, half the @Dijon mustard{2%tsp}, @sugar{1/4%tsp}, @Fry seasoning{1/4%tsp}, juice from one lemon wedge, @salt{1/2%tsp}, and @pepper{}.

> For 4 servings, use ½ tsp sugar, ½ tsp Fry Seasoning, juice from two lemon wedges, and 1 tsp salt.

== Patties ==

In a #medium bowl{}, gently combine @ground beef{10%oz}, remaining mustard, remaining @Fry seasoning{3/4%tsp}, a big pinch of salt, and pepper. Form beef into two equal-size balls (four balls for 4 servings).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Once pan is hot, add beef; firmly flatten each ball with a lightly oiled #spatula{} to create patties, each slightly wider than a burger bun. Cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> Don't worry if the patties aren't perfectly round—those irregular edges will turn crispy.

== Coleslaw ==

Meanwhile, in a second medium bowl, combine @coleslaw mix{4%oz}, remaining mayonnaise, remaining sour cream, @sugar{1/4%tsp}, juice from two lemon wedges, a pinch of salt, and pepper.

== Assembly ==

Halve @potato buns{2}; toast until golden.

Spread a thin layer of tangy mayo on bottom buns. Fill buns with patties, @crispy fried onions{1}, and as much remaining tangy mayo as you like.

Divide burgers and slaw between plates. (You can also top burgers with a bit of slaw for an authentic deli special.) Serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.